 whose novels are based on events in Canadian history. These sometimes startling conversations take the reader behind the scenes of the novels and into the minds of their authors. Through them we explore the writers’ motives for writing, the challenges they faced in gathering information and presenting it in fictional form, the sometimes hostile reaction they faced after publication, and, perhaps most interestingly, the stories that didn’t make it into their novels. Speaking in the Past Tense provides fascinating insights into the construction of national historical narratives and myths, both those familiar to us and those that are still being written.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistorical fiction, Canadian (English)xAuthorship. 0aHistorical fiction, Canadian (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aHistorical fiction, CanadianxAuthorship. 0aHistorical fiction, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 0aNovelists, Canadian (English)xInterviews. 0aNovelists, CanadianvInterviews. 0aNovelists, CanadianxInterviews. 0aRoman historique canadien-anglaisxArt d'écrire. 0aRoman historique canadien-anglaisxArt d'écrire. 0aRoman historique canadien-anglaisxHistoire et critique. 0aRomanciers canadiens-anglaisxEntretiensxKanada. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBoyden, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, George Elliott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrummey, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobertson, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStenson, Fred, econtrib